reviews.review_text:
25 around the sun
Growing out of Red Rocks initially caused them to abandon the region - it had been 3½ years. IIRC, there were no mail-order tix for any December shows except the NYE run. It wasn't hard to get into the AZ shows but all three Denver shows were tight. I had come close to doing the Europe tour, but it fell through on lack of commitment (seriously? from stoners?). So I was perked for these shows because I hadn't seen them in months (a long time in those days), because the September tapes had shown up and were hot, and because I had never seen them indoors in Denver and didn't know what to expect. Musically, the shows improve each night, with the third being a standout for '90. The cool thing about Colo at the time was that P-bud - a pungent Afghani descendant grown in the Paonia orchard valley - had a good harvest and was available. My fave of all time, other than Matanuska and original Maui, it had the landrace characteristics that are so hard to find in today's all-hybridized stun cannabis. These shows marked the Silver Anniversary for the band - the day before being 25yrs since they appeared at the Muir Beach acid test as the Grateful Dead (after dropping "The Warlocks", it was the first time they were billed as the Dead on a gig poster: 25 yrs earlier to the day). As such, I added Silver Anniversary logos to a couple of my T-shirt designs, trading in the lots with others that did the same, and now I still have 4 or 5 different shirts from these shows. We had first row in the close stands on this night, and security required a second ticket check. My wife had a bathroom break twice, but the second time she was gone a long time. Knowing how queues are for the Ladies', I waited quite awhile before going on the expedition. I found her standing in the tunnel, pointing at the angry nazi-guy that wouldn't let her back to her seat. "Oh no," he told me, "I've seen this ticket too many times. I know the scam." I had to find a Feyline manager to get her back to our seats, missing a bit of the show. It was hard enough getting tix in the first place. The 2hr second set makes up for a rough start - though some of the 1st sounds better on AUDs (my AUD copy is a from a source not on the Archive). The energy inside the Mac really lifted for the 2nd set (this show is mainly known for the China>Rider and the Dark Star). It was heady. I had a friend who worked for Feyline at the time, which somehow meant we could go to the band's hotel after the show. Bob had a reception/buffet room rented for people to mingle and had his own sound system on wheels for party music. He zeroed in on this cat, probably because he was not a DeadHead - one of a few in the room. Bob was just being cordial and hostly, but anytime my friend encountered this he made a sex thing out of it (after all, he also said the following about a pro athlete and another popular musician). For a few years afterward, every time the Dead were mentioned he'd pipe up with, "Did you know their guitarist is gay?" Life before the internet. First Set. Rough start. The mix is a shambles for Touch of Grey - just Jer, Vince and the drummers. It must have been bad onstage too, cuz they get very sloppy. I was always missing Greatest Story by one day, so I was chuffed; but it's a crap version. Bruce shows up part way, followed by Bobby guitar (loudly). Still no Phil. The mix improves for Candyman but the playing is tentative. Things first get solved for Walkin' Blues, though not much really happens until Loose Lucy. Here X factor hits the stalls. A good one; Jer does some independent study, adding a solo and repeating the 3rd verse instead of the fourth, and the rest listen closely, staying on their toes. It's a keys-heavy Mexicali, with Jer using horns MIDI. Maggie's was played 2 shows in a row (having recently returned). This one is strong. Jer teases Peggy-O, but gets nixed for a second Dylan. After Queen Jane he teases it again, but gets no bites (he won't get Peggy for two more nights) until he teases Deal. You may have to listen twice to get the insane brilliance on this set closer. Damn. Second Set. China Cat is kinda mellow/kinda delicious. The verses are switched but it has that X factor soaring, with Bruce having a lot to do with the superbness. Rider is a seriously beautiful version. Iko features dueling MIDI between accordion controller & guitar. Dark Star is only the 6th of '90 (and the 4th Vince/Bruce), so it was still special. Maybe not the best of the year, but a must-hear anyway, and more special for those doing the whole run, as the second verse is cleverly saved for the final night. One of my friends was less impressed because he had always missed Terrapin. He was patiently waiting for Dark Star to end muttering "c'mon Terrapin, c'mon Terrapin". I thought it unlikely and had to applaud his clairvoyance with a how-'bout-that face. As he stood transfixed we watched his face melt. Luckily he got a good one. Watchtower is typical for awhile, then gets better and better. Stella is a gilded version, with the Vince/Hornsby axis putting it over the top. That extra push, that energy, glides right into Throwing Stones - the best one since 3/29. 1st Set:  C+ 2nd Set: B Overall = 3½ stars Highlights: Deal - brilliance here China Cat Sunflower - delicious I Know You Rider - seriously beautiful Dark Star - special & bakes a treat for end of run Stella Blue - a perfect version with added keys Throwing Stones - best since 3/29 SOURCES: The 149736_UltraMatrix_sbd is the currently-best SBD, and is a remaster of miller_109289. The 2nd set is up on YouTube (forewarned: handheld, blurry, dark, and mostly just Jer).

A tale of two sets. Some shows are piping hot from start to finish. Others are highlighted by the first set. Others have a first set which more or less serves as a warmup for the second set. I find this show to be an example of the latter. This nine-song first set looks awesome on paper, and don’t get me wrong, it’s not bad by any means. A little pedestrian is all. Nothing you’d skip straight through, unless you’re really looking to cherry-pick.

The second set is the bee's knees. Electric, dramatic, incredible stuff. Heavy, hardcore Grateful Dead, which I’m sure was perfectly conducive to, and perhaps a product of, the atmosphere of an evening show held deep in the Colorado winter. Although this was a new lineup putting excitingly novel spins on most of what they were playing, there are certain moments that are downright old school. There are brutally gritty Garcia licks in this Dark Star that will tug your consciousness straight back in time to 1968. And it segues into Terrapin. Sheesh!

Garcia teases God Rest Ye Merry Gentlemen in Space, a clever seasonal tiding of joy. All Along the Watchtower and Stella Blue are also of note. Very powerful, weighty music on tap here folks. I’ll have to give the other shows from this Denver ‘90 run a try. This is one of the strongest second sets of a very good year.
